abstract: SYRACUSE, N.Y., June 30.--Henry Utasch left his home in Butternut-street at 4 o'clock yesterday morning and wandered to Round-top Hill. Sitting down among the bushes he pulled from his pocket a knife, closely resembling a three-corner file, and plunged it into his throat, inflicting a terrible gash. He then cut both wrists and stabbed himself eight times in the body. When he was found he was alive, but he died at 9 o'clock this evening.

abstract: TOULON, July 4.--Dr. Koch, a member of the German Cholera Committee, and head of the Cholera Commission, who has offered his services to the French Government to ascertain the character of the epidemic, has arrived here. abstract: ST. PAUL, Minn., July 6.--Reports from all quarters of the Red River Valley indicate the most favorable conditions for growing crops. It is estimated by many that the average yield will be 25 bushels per acre.

abstract: NORFOLK, Va., July 28.--News has reached this city of a terrible storm which struck the litele town of Edenton, N.C., on Saturday night. The path of the storm was only 200 yards wide, but it carried destruction before it. Several warehouses and storehouses were either blown down or unroofed, and a church was unroofed while the congregation of colored people were worshipping there, killing two little children. The damage to property is estimated at $40,000.
